[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] In computing, a **library** is a collection of resources that can be used during software development to implement a computer program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Commonly, a library consists of executable code such as compiled functions and classes, or a library can be a collection of source code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A resource library may contain data such as images and text.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A library can be used by multiple, independent consumers (programs and other libraries).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] This differs from resources defined in a program which can usually only be used by that program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] When a consumer uses a library resource, it gains the value of the library without having to implement it itself.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Libraries encourage software reuse in a modular fashion.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Libraries can use other libraries resulting in a hierarchy of libraries in a program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] When writing code that uses a library, a programmer only needs to know how to use that library's application programming interface (API) without understanding its internal mechanics.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] For example, a program could use a library that abstracts a complicated system call so that the programmer can use the system feature without spending time to learn the intricacies of the system function.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] The idea of a computer library dates back to the first computers created by Charles Babbage.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] An 1888 paper on his Analytical Engine suggested that computer operations could be punched on separate cards from numerical input.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] In 1947 Goldstine and von Neumann speculated that it would be useful to create a "library" of subroutines for their work on the IAS machine, an early computer that was not yet operational at that time.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] They envisioned a physical library of magnetic wire recordings, with each wire storing reusable computer code.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Inspired by von Neumann, Wilkes and his team constructed EDSAC.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A filing cabinet of punched tape held the subroutine library for this computer.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Programs for EDSAC consisted of a main program and a sequence of subroutines copied from the subroutine library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] In 1951 the team published the first textbook on programming, *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, which detailed the creation and the purpose of the library.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] COBOL included "primitive capabilities for a library system" in 1959, but Jean Sammet described them as "inadequate library facilities" in retrospect.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] JOVIAL has a Communication Pool (COMPOOL), roughly a library of header files.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Another major contributor to the modern library concept came in the form of the subprogram innovation of FORTRAN.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] FORTRAN subprograms can be compiled independently of each other, but the compiler lacked a linker.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] So prior to the introduction of modules in Fortran-90, type checking between FORTRAN subprograms was impossible.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] By the mid 1960s, copy and macro libraries for assemblers were common.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Starting with the popularity of the IBM System/360, libraries containing other types of text elements, e.g., system parameters, also became common.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] In IBM's OS/360 and its successors this is called a partitioned data set.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] The first object-oriented programming language, Simula, developed in 1965, supported adding classes to libraries via its compiler.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] The *linking* (or *binding*) process resolves references known as *symbols* (or *links*) by searching for them in various locations including configured libraries.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] If a linker (or binder) does not find a symbol, then it fails, but multiple matches may or may not cause failure.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Some references in a program or library module are stored in a relative or symbolic form which cannot be resolved until all code and libraries are assigned final static addresses.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Relocation is the process of adjusting these references, and is done either by the linker or the loader.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] In general, relocation cannot be done to individual libraries themselves because the addresses in memory may vary depending on the program using them and other libraries they are combined with.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] Position-independent code avoids references to absolute addresses and therefore does not require relocation.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] An executable library consists of code that has been converted from source code into machine code or an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A linker allows for using library objects by associating each reference with an address at which the object is located.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] For example, in C, a library function is invoked via C's normal function call syntax and semantics.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A variant is a library containing compiled code (object code in IBM's nomenclature) in a form that cannot be loaded by the OS but that can be read by the linker.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A static library is an executable library that is linked into a program at build-time by a linker (or whatever the build tool is called that does linking).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] This process, and the resulting stand-alone file, is known as a static build of the program.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A static build may not need any further relocation if virtual memory is used and no address space layout randomization is desired.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A static library is sometimes called an *archive* on Unix-like systems.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] A dynamic library is linked when the program is run – either at load-time or runtime.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/library-computing] The dynamic library was intended after the static library to support additional software deployment flexibility.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] A **network socket** is a software structure within a network node of a computer network that serves as an endpoint for sending and receiving data across the network.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The structure and properties of a socket are defined by an application programming interface (API) for the networking architecture.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Sockets are created only during the lifetime of a process of an application running in the node.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Because of the standardization of the TCP/IP protocols in the development of the Internet, the term *network socket* is most commonly used in the context of the Internet protocol suite, and is therefore often also referred to as **Internet socket**.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In this context, a socket is externally identified to other hosts by its **socket address**, which is the triad of transport protocol, IP address, and port number.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The term *socket* is also used for the software endpoint of node-internal inter-process communication (IPC), which often uses the same API as a network socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The use of the term *socket* in software is analogous to the function of an electrical female connector, a device in hardware for communication between nodes interconnected with an electrical cable.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Similarly, the term *port* refers to external physical endpoints at a node or device.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) for the network protocol stack creates a handle for each socket created by an application, commonly referred to as a *socket descriptor*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In Unix-like operating systems, this descriptor is a type of file descriptor.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] It is stored by the application process for use with every read and write operation on the communication channel.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] At the time of creation with the API, a network socket is bound to the combination of a type of network protocol to be used for transmissions, a network address of the host, and a port number.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Ports are numbered resources that represent another type of software structure of the node.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] They are used as service types, and, once created by a process, serve as an externally (from the network) addressable location component, so that other hosts may establish connections.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Network sockets may be dedicated for persistent connections for communication between two nodes, or they may participate in connectionless and multicast communications.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In practice, due to the proliferation of the TCP/IP protocols in use on the Internet, the term *network socket* usually refers to use with the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] It is therefore often also called **Internet socket**.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] An application can communicate with a remote process by exchanging data with TCP/IP by knowing the combination of protocol type, IP address, and port number.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] This combination is often known as a *socket address*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] It is the network-facing access handle to the network socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The remote process establishes a network socket in its own instance of the protocol stack and uses the networking API to connect to the application, presenting its own socket address for use by the application.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] A protocol stack, usually provided by the operating system (rather than as a separate library, for instance), is a set of services that allows processes to communicate over a network using the protocols that the stack implements.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The operating system forwards the payload of incoming IP packets to the corresponding application by extracting the socket address information from the IP and transport protocol headers and stripping the headers from the application data.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) that programs use to communicate with the protocol stack, using network sockets, is called a **socket API**.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Development of application programs that utilize this API is called *socket programming* or *network programming*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Internet socket APIs are usually based on the Berkeley sockets standard.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In the Berkeley sockets standard, sockets are a form of file descriptor, due to the Unix philosophy that "everything is a file", and the analogies between sockets and files.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Both have functions to read, write, open, and close.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In practice, the differences strain the analogy, and different interfaces (send and receive) are used on a socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In inter-process communication, each end generally has its own socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In the standard Internet protocols TCP and UDP, a socket address is the combination of an IP address and a port number, much like one end of a telephone connection is the combination of a phone number and a particular extension.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Sockets need not have a source address, for example, for only sending data, but if a program *binds* a socket to a source address, the socket can be used to receive data sent to that address.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Based on this address, Internet sockets deliver incoming data packets to the appropriate application process.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The distinctions between a socket (internal representation), socket descriptor (abstract identifier), and socket address (public address) are subtle, and these are not always distinguished in everyday usage.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Further, specific definitions of a *socket* differ between authors.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In IETF Request for Comments, Internet Standards, in many textbooks, as well as in this article, the term *socket* refers to an entity that is uniquely identified by the socket number.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In other textbooks, the term *socket* refers to a local socket address, i.e., a "combination of an IP address and a port number".
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In the original definition of *socket* given in RFC 147, as it was related to the ARPA network in 1971, *"the socket is specified as a 32-bit number with even sockets identifying receiving sockets and odd sockets identifying sending sockets."* Today, however, socket communications are bidirectional.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Within the operating system and the application that created a socket, a socket is referred to by a unique integer value called a *socket descriptor*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] On Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, the command-line tools netstat or ss are used to list established sockets and related information.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] This example in Java, modeled according to the Berkeley socket interface, sends the string "Hello, world!" via TCP to port `80` of the host with address `203.0.113.0`.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Each packet sent or received on a datagram socket is individually addressed and routed.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Order and reliability are not guaranteed with datagram sockets, so multiple packets sent from one machine or process to another may arrive in any order or might not arrive at all.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In order to receive broadcast packets, a datagram socket should not be bound to a specific address, though in some implementations, broadcast packets may also be received when a datagram socket is bound to a specific address.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] and unique flow of error-free data without record boundaries, with well-defined mechanisms for creating and destroying connections and reporting errors.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] On the Internet, stream sockets are typically implemented using TCP so that applications can run across any network using TCP/IP protocol.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Allow direct sending and receiving of IP packets without any protocol-specific transport layer formatting.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] according to the chosen transport layer protocol (e.g.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] When reading from a raw socket, the headers are usually included.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] When transmitting packets from a raw socket, the automatic addition of a header is optional.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] (APIs), for example, those based on Berkeley sockets, support raw sockets.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] interface, but three years later, Microsoft limited Winsock's raw socket support because of security concerns.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Other socket types are implemented over other transport protocols, such as Systems Network Architecture and Unix domain sockets for internal inter-process communication.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Computer processes that provide application services are referred to as servers, and create sockets on startup that are in the *listening state*.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] These sockets are waiting for initiatives from client programs.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] A TCP server may serve several clients concurrently by creating a unique dedicated socket for each client connection in a new child process or processing thread for each client.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] These are in the *established state* when a socket-to-socket virtual connection or virtual circuit (VC), also known as a TCP session, is established with the remote socket, providing a duplex byte stream.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] A server may create several concurrently established TCP sockets with the same local port number and local IP address, each mapped to its own server-child process, serving its own client process.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] They are treated as different sockets by the operating system since the remote socket address (the client IP address or port number) is different; i.e., since they have different socket pair tuples.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] UDP sockets do not have an *established state*, because the protocol is connectionless.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] A UDP server process handles incoming datagrams from all remote clients sequentially through the same socket.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] UDP sockets are not identified by the remote address, but only by the local address, although each message has an associated remote address that can be retrieved from each datagram with the networking application programming interface (API).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Local and remote sockets communicating over TCP are called **socket pairs**.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Each socket pair is described by a unique 4-tuple consisting of source and destination IP addresses and port numbers, i.e. of local and remote socket addresses.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] As discussed above, in the TCP case, a socket pair is associated on each end of the connection with a unique 4-tuple.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The term *socket* dates to the publication of RFC 147 in 1971, when it was used in the ARPANET.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Most modern implementations of sockets are based on Berkeley sockets (1983), and other stacks such as Winsock (1991).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The Berkeley sockets API in the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) originated with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system as an API.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Only in 1989, however, could UC Berkeley release versions of its operating system and networking library free from the licensing constraints of AT&T's copyright-protected Unix.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] 1987, AT&T introduced the STREAMS-based Transport Layer Interface (TLI) in UNIX System V Release 3 (SVR3). and continued into Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Other early implementations were written for TOPS-20, MVS, VM, IBM-DOS (PCIP).
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] The socket is primarily a concept used in the transport layer of the Internet protocol suite or session layer of the OSI model.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Networking equipment such as routers, which operate at the internet layer, and switches, which operate at the link layer, do not require implementations of the transport layer.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] However, stateful network firewalls, network address translators, and proxy servers keep track of active socket pairs.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] In multilayer switches and quality of service (QoS) support in routers, packet flows may be identified by extracting information about the socket pairs.
[src:poco-cpp-lib/network-socket] Raw sockets are typically available in network equipment and are used for routing protocols such as IGRP and OSPF, and for Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).
